segments.text: assigned a job.
So he took care of us and showed us around the city.
It's a typical Chinese city.
It does have many more tall buildings in it, like a typical forested city.
I think of it sort of like Hong Kong.
It has a huge building right at the confluence of the Yangtze and some other river.
I forget the name of it.
It runs into the Yangtze River right there.
Maybe Yellow River or something.
Right at the confluence.
deep canyons into these riverbeds, huge deep canyons.
Oh, the rivers look like the Mississippi River, don't they?
And there's caves in the hillside.
It's very hilly on the mountains.
And not rock, yeah, but sort of like a limestone.
And there's just innumerable number of caves and holes and revetments and bomb shelters all throughout the city.
And we're, you know, the people who've been going for years because we haven't even bombed it yet.
They were used to it.
And sirens, the wailing sirens, you know, for bomb alerts and all.
The business was sort of as usual, you know, in China.
People were used to it.
Again, like ants for many of them, just millions of people.
And, of course, we'd drive in.
There were other American cars there.
I don't remember seeing any other Americans there.
in the place, except at the embassy I met General Burton, Army Air Corps, Air Force officer at that time, major.
No, he was a general at that time.
I had an interview with him trying to get a regular commission in the Air Force.
I determined to get that regular commission in the Air Force.
What did he say?
You ever hear of General Bruce Holloway, who commanded SAC before he retired?
Bruce Holloway is a very close friend of mine.
He was a major then, and he was with the American military mission into China.
That's the first time I met him.
We knew that pretty soon the AVD was going to be dissolved, or the Air Force was going to take us over.
Many of us were talking about, well, we'd be staying.
China and go in the Air Force there, or did we have a belly full of stuff and want to go home, or what?
And we were continuing talking about it, and everybody had a different opinion.
The only thing, I want to do anything that would get me a regular commission.
That's what I want to do.
So you went in and talked to him?
So I asked for a conference with General Burton through Bruce Holloway, and I went in, he gave me a conference, I went in and sat down and talked to him.
I guess I explained the situation and talked to him about 30 minutes.
Very attentive, just as nice as he could be.
When I got through, his only comment, he says, well, and I think he called me just Mr.
Bond.
Yeah, I wasn't.
I was out of the military as Mr.
Bond.
I'm sorry, I understand what you're saying, but only Congress can do what you want to do.
In other words, you take a congressional act to give me a regular commission.
I said, well, if that's the way it is, I think I'll just go on home.
I was very disappointed and a little bit mad.
I could see my plan, I could see my plan going to the dogs.
Here I was, already almost a double ace, combat experience, shot down once, and still had scars on my face.
The Air Force building up now, and the experience and all.
So, old Bruce Holloway later on told me, I met him
years later, and he told me that when I left, he said, General Byrne came out and he said, there is a man that really wants a regular commission.
And get back to the city, that's, we had ice cream there for the first time, had ice cream and hamburgers, and that was out of this world, and then
Again, we stayed on alert there for a while, but did nothing and pretty soon it got boring.
I saw the old man a lot up there because it was for international planning and strategy and war playing and all between the nations was going on.
Now they were free from Japanese bombing, so the old man did most of his work there.
It was soon after that that we had to get into it again.
The old man laid a plan on it, of course, to go down to Kwai Lin with another trick.
Okay, now where's that?
Kwai Lin is here.
Okay, that's...
It's southeast of Chongqing.
K-W-E-I-L-I-N.
Okay, that is... Down toward Hong Kong.
Toward Canton and Hong Kong.
All right.
Okay, now what was...
When was that and what was the plan?
So the idea of that was, as I told you, the Japanese had reoriented their strategy to take China from the coast and just hold what they had in Burma.
So they started to drive.
They were already in the northern part of China, and they started to drive from the
That says Wuhan.
It's a toilet drive from the Wuhan, W-H-A-N area.
It was called another name then.
Anyway.
And their drive was toward Chongqing?
They were going to drive straight down and take Wei Lin.
Oh, they were moving south.
And split this part from that part.
Because the rail, the big rail head, goes all the way down to Southeast Agency.
Okay, so they were going to take down.
So that would split off China.
Hancao.
Hancao was the name of that, Wuhan.
Okay, and so that would cut off... That split China.
Yeah, north and south.
Okay.
Okay.
And we were going to...
The plan was to move most of its forces...
and I do mean most of them, to Hualien.
Now, this was a huge air base that the Chinese had been building for some time, just like the huge one-way, and I told you about it, Kunming, in expectation of eventually having bombers there.
The old man planted that.
It was an ideal, beautiful layout for operations of aircraft, except only the one-way approach to the field.
The other end was these huge mountains there.
It looked like ice cream cones turned upside down all over it.
It's a beautiful, luxurious valley.
It's where they usually take the VIP visitors to see part of China.
They take them down that river.
That's where Nixon was taken, by the way, when he visited China.
Beautiful area, and a very big industrial city.
And it's where a lot of the refugees from Hong Kong came up into the Japanese coast.
Not Hong Kong, but Canton.
They came back and went in.
and a key railroad center north and south.
That railroad center is the line of communications that the Japanese were going to come right straight on down through into Hanoi.
I mean, French Indochina, then split China north and south and separate the east and west.

And the old man was, well, he needed air power to help, and we were going to supposedly, you know, again, hold off the Japanese Air Force, at least to keep them from giving air support to their troops.
and bombing and strafing the Chinese troops.
And again, it was going to turn out to be an air battle for the supremacy of the air before you could even do that.
So we laid the plan on to sneak our aircraft, and I think there we took about 20 aircraft.
No.
I think it's 12 aircraft.
12 aircraft, 12 P-40.
Again, Bob Neal and I would take the South Coast down.
Okay, when was it?
went to Quail Inn on the 11th of June.
And how many planes went down there?
Did you tell me?
I think I told you it was twelve, and I believe that's true.
The whole idea was
Well, on his first fight, on the 12th of June, we had 12 aircraft up in the air.

The whole idea was to slip in there late in the evening, and again, come in low altitude late in the evening, and where the Japanese and their spies wouldn't know about it, and here again, be up in the air the next morning to catch the Japanese bombers, the training crews who were running daily training missions,
in that area, Hualien, Heng Yang, Ling Ling area, bombing up and down a railroad track, you know, on training missions out of Hanoi.
They were training a Japanese crew.
And then we'd be ready to catch them, you know, and they'd be completely helpless, unsuspecting, surprising.
That was the plan.
So we took 12 airplanes down that evening and went to bed early and was ready the next morning on alert.
It so happened that the Japanese learned our stuff, and they knew that we were down there, and they had their own plan that we later on found out very rapidly.
Anyway, we took off that morning when, sure enough, here comes the flight, bombing flight, bombers coming from Manoa.
So we took off, and I was leading the attack flight.

I was leading a flight, I had a flight of three, no four, my staff was four, P-40Es at 15,000 feet, the attack flight, and up behind me at 18,000 feet was another four, and then at 20,000 feet was Bob Neal in reserve with four aircraft, so we had 12 airplanes, and in my flight I had this
the brand new E's with 6.50 caliber guns firing out the wing roots.
What I mean today is just going to blast it out of the air.
It is fantastic.
6.50's hitting something.
So you were at 18,000 feet, right?
And where were the bombers?
And sure enough, here come the bombers in at about my level, 15,000 feet.
But then you see we had Bob and the others up at 18,000 feet, so we had some airplanes above us.
But old Charlie Bond was in the attack flight, and that would be the same altitude.
Well, I didn't see him at first, but my wingman, Joe Rosberg,
We had a regular Air Force communication set.
We could talk to each other for a change.
Clearly hear each other.
So he called me and told me, he said, right in front of each other, right in front of you.
And sure enough, coming at an angle, we'd come about like this.
And an angle, matter of fact, we'd call him just about like this.
I forget what position it was with respect to the field at that time, but at any rate, I was closer here.
So you were coming up from the left?
Right, from the left rear.
And about the same altitude, and I said, oh, I see him, I see him.
And here we were, four ships in attack formation, so of course we told Bob Neal and all that.
And that's all the airplanes I could see.
I think there were four of them in formation.
Four bombers.
Yeah, four bombers in a B formation.
Oh, five.
Matter of fact, Joe Roberts flew up on my wing and fired his gun to get my attention and directed a fight of five Japanese bombers to my lower right.
I had almost committed my formation to a jet formation at my left front, and I saw another one.
So we knew there were two formations of aircraft.
I chose this one.
Which one's this one?
This one is to the lower right.
So because I'm in a better position, I had a little bit of altitude on him.
And I figured that I could just ease down in position and just start on this left guy.
and go right through those four and just shoot all four of them down just like that.
Fully confident with this, these terrible firepower of 650.
Well, I closed, started closing in and started firing, and I probably fired too far away.
I had to be, it must have been at least a thousand yards, 50 calories, and I figured I'd start closing in.
And I knew they had rear gunners.
And I started closing in, and I got closer and closer and closer.
And I was close enough to see the rear gunner's bay down.
It was a bay that hung down at the bottom of the gun sticking out.
And I knew they were firing at me because I could see the smoke trailing from the gun.
And then all of a sudden, I caught it in my vision.
My yellow crystalline light warning came on.
And I looked down.
And then I looked a little closer, and smoke began to curl out from behind my dashboard, from my instrument board.
And I said, oh, no, I've had it again.
So I told Joe I was going to pull it off.
So I pulled down because I knew I had trouble.
I had an amazing dawn on me.
I had to have been hit with a return fire.
My press cone system had gone out.
And about that time, I looked up.
And again, you know, see where I was, bummers and all, and I saw these fighters, Japanese fighters.
It must have been about 10 or 12, little I-97s.
I saw them swarming down, coming down on us, you know.
So this was their plan.
They had suspected this, and they had to escort, fighter escort, come in a little bit later, and much higher than usual.
I don't think Bob Neal at 20,000 feet ever saw the fighters, because nobody got on them.
They came down immediately on me.
And obviously, you know, press tone light on.
Obviously, I was putting on steam out of my press tone system at the rear of my airplane.
So, you know, you always go after the wounded guy.
As I pulled off, two of these fighters came down and began to close on me.
Well, I knew that, you know, eventually my engine was going to freeze up.
So I said, well, I nursed as long as I can.
So I was torn between the desire of pushing full throttle and a steep dive to get away from them
I knew I could out-dive them, the little ones.
They had a thermal blaster on about 320 miles an hour.
And I could easily hit 450.
But at the same time, I knew that the more I sped up my engine, the less time I was going to have it.
And I made the prop throws.
It'd be like putting a big plywood of 4x8 right out in front of me and slowing me down as I was beat for them.
So I was torn between, so I kept it, I got up to about 375, just a little under 400, and sure enough began to pull away from it, but not before they put the bullet holes in my wing.
And I saw the metal curl up in the wings and the bullets went through them, but I didn't catch on fire.
And I, of course, I was crouched behind that fire, the armor plate, and I, you know, only about two months ago, I guess, was I shot down.
Sure.
So...
I admit I was a little bit scared, and I was wondering if old Torrey Bond hadn't had it.
But I kept looking, you know, I looked back at the time, and finally they pulled away.
And I thought, well, at least they pulled off my danger.
Then I began to look, and I knew I was near our field.
I looked down the field way off to the right, but I could see it.
I was still probably about six or eight thousand feet.
And I saw a Japanese fighter straight from the field.
I said, oh, I can't go in there.
And I said, well, what do I do?
What choice did you have?
I said, well, I'm going to crash land this thing.
I'm going to bail out.
And about that time, the prop just stopped.
The whole engine just froze, and the propeller stopped.
Just, you know, burn up.
The metal just queued.
And of course, it meant it stopped.
Well, then that's just like putting air brakes on.
I began to slow up, and then I had to
lower my nose.
I was a glider from then on.
And I forgot about, you know, when engine not running, I didn't have any hydraulic pressure.
That operated my flaps with my little finger on the stick.
Put my flaps down where I could, you know, come in slow for landing, but I forgot about this.
I wouldn't have that capability to let my flaps down.
But my engine did, and I picked out a field I was going to land in, rice paddy area, and left my gear up, and I was all prepared to land.
And
As I was coming in, getting ready to slow up, I hit my little finger on the wheel to put the flap down, but no flaps, and I just continued right on.
And I saw I was going to overshoot.
How fast were you going?
Oh, it must have been 100, 105, something like that, 110.
And I just continued at that speed.
I didn't slow down any whatsoever.
And you overshot your field?
Oh, I knew I was going to overshoot.
I knew what happened.
I didn't have any flaps, so I couldn't slow down.
If I remember correctly, you had to be around 100 at absolute max speed before you stalled.
Did you light your gas on?
Uh-huh.
Was there any way to get rid of all your extra gas?
Oh, I didn't have time to do anything like that.
As a matter of fact, I didn't even think.
All I thought about was landing airplanes.
For some reason or other, I didn't want to bail out.
I still don't know why.
I just
I guess it was having done it before.
But thinking about it, all of a sudden I was too low to bail out.
And here I'd overshot that field.
So at the final moment, and at that very low speed, I took a chance and made almost a vertical bank.
I couldn't have been over 50 feet from the ground.
And pulled in tightly to hit in a rice paddy area immediately to my left.
It's one I didn't install, but it didn't.
But just as I rolled out flat, I hit the rice paddy area.
And it so happened I hit, went in a little bit steeper than I thought, and I bounced.
And thank God I bounced because I bounced up to the next, I was going up terrace, rice paddy areas.
And I bounced up over about a three or four foot hard dike mud little dam
Just tangent with the next layer, and came in on that, and then I caught into the mud and slime, of course.
I stopped in about 50 feet.
But had I gone on and landed where I first hit, I'd have hit that mud dike, and oh, I'd have killed myself.
Just like we had another guy do that one time before.
Mangelberg would be landed against one of them, and boy, it's like brick, like stone.
But as I hit the cockpit,
I had the canopy open.

The canopy flew forward and kept all the mud and stuff off of me, but my head flew forward in the deceleration and caught my forehead on the gun sight and tore a little of my scalp open there, just scalp open, and didn't even, well, it stunned me a little bit, didn't knock me out, and when I clicked my senses, I immediately rolled the canopy open and unstrapped and got the hell out of the airplane.
Here it might catch fire.
and got out on the wing because there was mud around them.
And the front end of the airplane, the propeller, the gearbox, and part of the motor had torn off.
It was laying about 10 or 15 feet further up from the airplane.
And the metal was just blue.
It was burned up so that you could smell burnt metal and all.
At any rate, they got out.
And they didn't look around.
Did you get away from the plane?
I didn't want to get away from the airplane first because, you know, I'd step in mud up to my knees.
And the first thing I was- What about blowing up or Japanese coming down?
Well, I looked for straight from Japanese, and then I remember they left me at probably three or four thousand feet, so I may be harmed.
So I wasn't too worried about that.
But I looked around and saw all these Chinese peasants in the field with pitchforks and all, you know.
digging at the rice, and I got to thinking about my other experience.
I thought, well, am I going to go through the same thing again?
These guys got pitchforks in their hands.

So I didn't know what to do for a moment, but I just stood on a wingtip, and I, like you say, I was a little concerned about maybe the airplane would blow up, but then nothing happened, and as the seconds went by, I
I'd forgotten about being alarmed about that.
I just put on a wingtip.
Then I began to do my telephone pattern mind with a couple of nearer guys, Chinese peasants.
And the general wanted to have walked over, and I explained.
And I believe I had, oh.
Oh, did you ask them?
I showed them the Chinese emblem on the wing of the airplane.
So they knew I was no enemy.

I, you know, gave this deal, telephone, telephone, you know, and they point over across to the rice paddy area to a little building, same sort of layout before, you know, a group of buildings, and I, well, I've got to walk through this mud after all, and I had another pair of boots on, so I decided to at least save a parachute, so I took my parachute out of the seat and my Form 1,

and still had my helmet on, so I started walking through the mud, walked over this place, and came across another Chinese guy on the phone, and then he motioned for me to get the phone, and I got on the phone, and lo and behold, I heard English at the other end.
No kidding.
And it was a Catholic father missionary.
that I have to go through here in the diary to get his name.
But he told me who he was, and then I explained to him what the situation was.

He told me, he said, well, one of the men there, and I'll talk to him later on, he put him back, but one of the men there will bring you to my house in Yen Phu, Y-E-N-P-H-U, just south of Wayland, about 20 or 30 miles.
That's where I knew where I was.
But it so turned out I had to walk about ten miles to get to that place over a mountain ridge and across the river carrying that parachute.
But after I got off I gave it back to Chinaman.
He told Chinaman how to do this and all that.
And then most of them would come.
He didn't offer to carry a parachute or anything.
So we started walking and we walked over a mountain ridge and stopped a little bit every now and then and got to this river.
And they had a boat there that went across the river.
maybe 300 feet wide, and walked a little bit further and came to a town, a little town, and walked me up to this missionary's home.
And he immediately looked at my head, just bleeding a little, put his hands around me, and then the next thing I know, he had the mayor there, and I was a hero.
Oh, really?
And this goes into another story.
Now, mind you, this was after
being in combat and being shot down a second time, and actually I was a little shaken up.

And then here all of a sudden, thrust into this group of civilians that wanted to welcome me with a function of being a hero, and give me a wine and dine me, and I'm wanting to get back, you know, to a base at Guilin, and I'm frustrated and confused and all, and hurting a little.
But after maybe
30, 40 minutes, they did decide to take me to the railroad station.
I guess they were waiting for a train that was on schedule.
Put me on a train, take me up to Quail Inn.
All these were on the railroad.
But on the way up the train, they gave me what's called a firecracker parade for a hero.
And I'm telling you, it was worse than combat.
And I tell you, you know, all the time I fly, the weather's covered all.
And they got oil on the bottom all the time.
Well, you know, the Chinese invented firecrackers.
And they're a great mentality.
And as I was going down the city, the word got around.
It was a small place, not near as big as Austin.
And I'd say about like Bonham, something like that.
But I'll bet there must have been 100,000 people around.
And the word got out, and they lined up and down the main street on the way to the railroad station.
And two Chinese soldiers would walk along in front of me, and they had these groups of firecrackers in those trains, little ones, fortunately.
Lady hookers.
You know, clusters of them.
They'd throw them in the middle of the street, and they'd start busting, you know, and they'd fly loose, and the others would bust, you know.
And I was this missionary, and a mayor was walking down that way, and I said, Walt, some of them, you know, would bust right under my leg and fly up my leg, between a couple of legs.
And I had burnt places all over my legs the time I got to train.
You know, you get blessed.
You were a tippy-toe.
But...
You know, it was one of those things where you couldn't do anything about it.
And when I got the train, they put me on.
Well, what did the people think in that little city?
This is probably the first time they've ever seen an apartment.
Well, the best I could understand, you know, there's no doubt they were welcoming a hero and a missionary explained, you know, that he'd been here 20 years.
He said, these people never seen anything like this.
He said, I assure you that what y'all are doing here, you know, he gave me up.
And that they all know it, and they appreciate it, and these people worship you, and you're God, and all.
And we had been given a supplement that we were given.
We stayed there about, well, I stayed there until I came home in August.
They gave us parties and all.
So you stayed there.
Yeah.
Okay, so you got back on the train.
Yeah, and then that train took me on up to Quail Inn and stopped at Quail Inn.
When I got off there, Bob Neal met me and took me out to pee.
Only old man was there.
Uh-huh.
Question also.
Yeah.
When I got off, I had the bandage on my head, and he looked at me and said, Charlie?
He said, what's happened to your luck?
Or something.
What's happened to your luck?
You haven't been very lucky lately.
He said, it's the second time they got you.
And I said, yeah.
And he said, well, I ate pee all night.
I told him I was sorry I lost the airplane.
I told him what happened.
He said, don't worry about it.
I said, we're glad you're back.
You know, words like that.
Of course, he was in the middle of playing another campaign, and that's the reason he was there.
So, after a few more minutes, he took me to the hospital, and then we just was critiquing the fight.
Well, of course, they'd already critiqued it, but Bob Neal began to critique me on it.
And what happened in the fight?
The Japanese, like I say, earlier, had told you, you know, they...
knew we were coming, that would be there, and they expected me.
They had their surprise.
Well, it so happened the flight I attacked was the bombers, and it was the bait.
The bait for all of us.
And I attacked it, and then the fighters came down on us.
But the other flight was in the formation of the bomber flight.
I think it was six of those.
I didn't prepare it with that.
Or five or six.
But these weren't bombers.
They were in a bomber formation.
And when Bob Neal...
No, a George Burgard flight attacked them, and Bob Neal eventually joined in with them.
They pulled up into Immelman's twin-engine aircraft and turned back and, you know, were practically on the tail of the P-40 when you knew what was going on.
It so happened this was the brand-new, I think it was called an I-97, twin-engine fighter that the Japanese built.
It was the first time we ever saw it.
These were fighters, and they had 20-millimeter guns in them.
Were they fast?
Oh, yeah.
Well, they were comparable to a P-40.
Actually, not as maneuverable as a P-40 because they're bigger and twin-engine.
And actually, they had a rear gunner on it.
It wasn't a real fighter per se.
Sort of a combo.
Yeah.
More of an attack airplane.
At any rate, very maneuverable.
But not as maneuverable as a Zero.
And after George Burgoyne and his flight, the boys would gain the sense that they knew then that they were up against fighters.

I think they shot one of them down, and later on we, well, as a matter of fact, the Chinese recovered the crew where the thing belly landed and captured the gunner, and we brought the gunner back to our air base where we actually had a chance to talk with him to an interpreter.
He was scared to death.
He was scared?
He was scared to death.
And he wanted to know where the bar power for the Tiger came from, so we showed him the gun.
Oh, really?
He showed the Japanese prisoner the guns?
Yeah.
What did he think of that?
Oh, well, he was impressed.
To the interpreter, that was the only question he asked.
Where is all your firepower from the Flying Tiger airplane?
We showed it to him.
And then we wanted to take him up to the cave.
We had our operations officer in a cave in one of these big mountains.
The interpreter told the Chinese army guys to bring him up to a cave in North Ferry.
He looked up at the cave.
He thought he had it then.
He didn't want to go.
He was scared to death.
They thought, sure, he was going to take him up there and kill him.
But finally, he went.
Of course, he had to go.
And we took him up there, and the Italian people grilled him then.
But this is one way we learned about their plan, from him telling us.
And what did they do with this Japanese prisoner?
I don't know.
They took him off later on.
I'm sure they gave him to war.
I'm sure they did.
The Chinese had no mercy with Japanese prisoners.
And then I had that to recuperate.
And then I was back flying, though, in another few days.
That was just a hickey on my head.
Sure.
I think I was off about four or five days.
And then, sure enough, we began to get in a lot of aerial dogfights from the Handcow area.
And the United States Air Force, about that time, Army Air Corps, brought in a squadron of B-25s, bombers.
First time we ever had any bombers.
We went and escorted them.
And then we started that phase of operations, trying to escort the B-25s.
A brand new outfit that had no combat experience at all.
And that was quite an experience.
It was quite disheartening at first.
They were green guys, and they couldn't even find their targets.
But it basically turned out to be a very capable outfit.
Now, these were part of the Army Air Corps.
That's right, the Americans.
Okay, so these were the Americans in there, and they were just working with the Flying Tigers.
We were an escort.
And who was the general in charge?
Well, they were C under Chenault.
At that time, Chenault had already been inducted back into the Air Force.
And for all practical purposes, the 14th Air Force was organized on paper anyhow.
And this outfit was signed to him.
He was a brigadier general in the Army Air Corps at that time.
Okay, and so the Flying Tiger pilots, though, they were still civilian.
Oh, yeah.
And the bomber pilots were Army Air Corps.
That's right.
And we knew at that time, by that time, that some, probably July the 4th.
Summer of 42 then.
Summer of 42.
And we knew by then that around July the 4th of thereabouts, we figured in a minute's time that we would be disbanded.
And it was during that time at Quail Inn where all of us were interviewed by a team from the United States Army Air Corps with the idea of,
trying to get us to stay and inducting us as lieutenants and so forth.
Oh, okay.
So then sometime after Chong King, then you were interviewed to be given... Well, at Guilin I was interviewed, yes.
To be given.
And tell me about that.
Was the idea here to interview you, try to get you to stay there, and give you an act of commission?
What General Arnold's...
half-Arnold's objective was.

The last combat, the last Japanese I saw, this was about, I guess, a week or ten days before I left China to come home.

fuel light turned on in the airplane, indicating, you know, fuel, no fuel.
